Practical No. 8
Aim: Linear Regression Using R
Theory:
(A) Create a relationship model and get the coefficient.
# Values of height
x <- c(151, 174, 138, 186, 128, 136, 179, 163, 152, 131)
# Values of weight
y <- c(63, 81, 66, 91, 47, 57, 76, 72, 62, 68)
# Apply the lm() function
relation <- lm(y ~ x)
print(relation)
(B) Get the summary of relationship
print(summary(relation))
(C) Predict the weight of new person
Syntax: predict(object, newdata)
object - It is the formula which is already created using lm() function.
newdata - It is the vector containing new value for predictor variable.
Find the weight of the person with height 170:
a <- data.frame(x = 170)
result <- predict(relation, a)
print(result)
(D) Visualize the regression graphically
png(file = "linearregression.png")
# Plot the chart
plot(y, x, col = "blue", main = "Height & Weight Regression",
xlab = "Weight in kg", ylab = "Height in cm")
abline(lm(x ~ y), cex = 1.3, pch = 16)
# Save the file
dev.off()
Conclusion:
In this practical, a linear regression model was successfully created using R to analyze the
relationship between height and weight. The lm() function helped in identifying the correlation and
coefficients between the variables.
